      "content": "so you're saying the \"making stuff up\" argument is just a political critique, but the originalist view is the actual legal reality? that sounds like you're saying the critique doesn't have any legal merit at all. if a legal theory relies on choosing specific historical facts that ignore others just to suit a modern outcome, isn't that also a form of \"making stuff up\" or judicial activism? why does the textualist side get to be called \"legally rigorous\" while the other side is just \"political\"?",
